        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house if they get SNAP benefits?",
            "answer": "Yes. The primary home and the lot it sits on don't count toward the $4,500 asset limit for seniors. Your parent can own their home outright and still qualify."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's Social Security is just over the income limit?",
            "answer": "They may still qualify. Alaska allows a $358 standard deduction, plus 20% off any earned income, plus medical expenses over $35/month, plus shelter costs up to $1,189. These deductions often bring gross income below the qualifying threshold."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can SNAP benefits be used for pet food or vitamins?",
            "answer": "No. SNAP only covers food for human consumption. You cannot use SNAP for alcohol, tobacco, vitamins, medicines, pet food, cleaning supplies, or hot prepared foods."
          },
          {
            "question": "How long does SNAP certification last for seniors?",
            "answer": "If your parent qualifies for ESAP (Elderly Simplified Application Project), certification lasts 36 months with no regular check-in interviews. Standard SNAP certification is 24 months with periodic reviews."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if my parent's income changes after approval?",
            "answer": "Report major changes like new work income or lottery winnings over $4,500. Small changes in Social Security or pension amounts typically don't need to be reported immediately, especially under ESAP rules."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent get SNAP if they live with me?",
            "answer": "It depends on whether you buy and prepare food together. If your parent buys and cooks their own food separately, they can apply as a one-person household. If you share meals and grocery shopping, the whole household's income counts."
          }
        ],
