        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house if she qualifies for ALTCS?",
            "answer": "Yes, if it's her primary Arizona residence and the home equity is under $752,000 (2026 limit). The house is exempt from the asset limits as long as she lives there or intends to return."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if Dad's income is just over the $2,901 limit?",
            "answer": "He won't qualify for ALTCS. The income limits are strict — $2,901/month for a single person in 2025. However, limits are updated each January, so check current amounts when applying."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does my parent need to be in a nursing home already to apply?",
            "answer": "No. Your parent can apply from home, assisted living, or anywhere else. ALTCS will assess their care needs and determine the appropriate level of services."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if we make a mistake on the application?",
            "answer": "Automatic denial. ALTCS requires error-free applications. Consider having a family member, attorney, or Medicaid planning service help complete the paperwork."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much of my parent's care will ALTCS actually cover?",
            "answer": "ALTCS covers all medically necessary long-term care services based on your parent's individual care plan — this could be full nursing home costs, assisted living fees, or home care hours as needed."
          },
          {
            "question": "If my parents are married, do both need to qualify?",
            "answer": "No. Only the spouse needing care must meet the medical and age requirements. The community spouse (staying at home) has different asset protections, determined case-by-case."
          }
        ],
