        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "What if my parent was denied LIHEAP before?",
            "answer": "Reapply now. Michigan expanded eligibility rules and no longer requires a State Emergency Relief decision letter. Your parent may now qualify under the new 60% State Median Income limit or through automatic qualification if they receive programs like SNAP or Medicaid."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent get help if their utilities aren't shut off yet?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent doesn't need to wait for shut-off. They qualify if they have a past-due bill, received a shut-off notice, or are falling behind on a payment plan. LIHEAP is designed to prevent shut-offs, not just respond to them."
          },
          {
            "question": "What's the difference between LIHEAP and other energy assistance programs?",
            "answer": "LIHEAP is crisis-focused for emergencies like shut-off notices, while Michigan's MEAP program offers broader energy assistance. Some utilities also offer their own assistance programs. You can apply for multiple programs — they don't conflict with each other."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much money will my parent actually receive?",
            "answer": "Grant amounts aren't fixed — they vary based on your parent's specific need, household size, and available funding in your area. The program covers what's needed for the crisis: past-due amounts, reconnection fees, or deliverable fuel costs."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if our utility company opted out of Michigan's energy assistance programs?",
            "answer": "Utilities that opt out of LIEAF (Low Income Energy Assistance Fund) must provide equivalent assistance through their own programs. They also must offer Winter Protection Plans preventing shut-offs from November 1 through April 15."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent apply if they live in subsidized housing?",
            "answer": "Yes, as long as they're responsible for their own utility bills. If utilities are included in rent, they wouldn't qualify for utility assistance, but they might qualify for help with deliverable fuels like propane if they use them for heating."
          }
        ],
