        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "What if Mom is a renter — can she still get weatherization services?",
            "answer": "Yes, but her landlord must give written permission and sign the Weatherization Assistance Program Owner/Landlord Agreement. The improvements benefit the property, so some landlords are willing to approve it."
          },
          {
            "question": "Her house was weatherized years ago through a different program. Does that disqualify her?",
            "answer": "Only if it was weatherized through this specific WAP program in the last 15 years (or since 2006 in some areas). Weatherization through utility companies or other programs doesn't count."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if the energy audit finds problems that disqualify the home?",
            "answer": "Major structural issues like roof damage, mold, dangerous electrical wiring, or missing windows will disqualify the home. WAP doesn't fix these problems — your parent would need to address them first through other resources."
          },
          {
            "question": "She gets Social Security but also has a small pension. Will that put her over the income limit?",
            "answer": "All household income counts, including Social Security, pensions, and any other sources. However, if she receives SSI (not regular Social Security), SDA, or FIP benefits, she's automatically income-eligible regardless of other income."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much will this actually save on her energy bills?",
            "answer": "There's no guarantee of specific savings because services vary based on the energy audit. Some homes get major improvements like furnace replacement and full insulation, while others may only get minor air sealing and weatherstripping."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can she apply if her income is slightly over the limit?",
            "answer": "No, income limits are firm. However, limits vary by county — Wayne Metro uses 1-month income while most other areas use 3-month averages, so timing of application might matter if her income fluctuates."
          }
        ],
