        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house if she qualifies for this waiver?",
            "answer": "Yes, as long as her home equity doesn't exceed $752,000 (2026 limit) and she lives there or intends to return. The home is completely exempt from the $2,000 asset limit if she, her spouse, or a dependent child under 21 lives there."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if Dad's income is just over $2,901 per month?",
            "answer": "He won't qualify for this waiver. Nevada uses strict income limits at 300% of the Federal Benefit Rate ($2,901 for individuals in 2025) with no spend-down option for this program."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does having dementia automatically qualify my parent?",
            "answer": "No. Your parent must demonstrate they need hands-on help with at least 3 specific daily activities during the functional assessment. The evaluator scores 13 areas including medication management, bathing, dressing, and mobility — dementia diagnosis alone isn't enough."
          },
          {
            "question": "How long will we wait after approval before services actually start?",
            "answer": "It varies. Even after both agencies approve eligibility, you may join a waitlist if Nevada has filled all available waiver slots. The research shows approved applicants often wait additional weeks or months before services begin."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if my parents are married but only one needs the waiver?",
            "answer": "Good news: if only one spouse applies, the other spouse's income doesn't count toward the $2,901 monthly limit. But if both spouses need the waiver, their combined income must stay under $5,802/month."
          },
          {
            "question": "What services will the waiver actually provide?",
            "answer": "The waiver covers case management, in-home personal care, homemaker services, adult day care, emergency response systems, chore services, and respite care. Your parent must use at least one service monthly, and the specific services depend on their assessed needs."
          }
        ],
