        "intro": "If your parent is struggling to afford groceries on a fixed income, SNAP provides monthly benefits loaded onto an EBT card that works like a debit card at grocery stores. The average benefit for households with older adults in New York City is $180/month, not the $16 minimum many seniors assume they'll get.\n\nBecause your parent is 60+, they qualify for expanded eligibility rules in New York — higher income limits and no asset limits if their income is under 200% of the federal poverty level ($2,608/month for one person). New York has expanded eligibility beyond federal requirements, so your parent may qualify even if other websites suggest they don't.\n\nMany seniors don't apply because they assume they won't qualify or will only get minimum benefits. Only about half of eligible seniors actually receive SNAP benefits, missing out on an average of $2,160 per year in grocery assistance.",
