          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house and savings if they get SNAP?",
            "answer": "Yes. If your parent's income is under 200% of the federal poverty level ($2,608/month for one person), there are no asset limits — they can own their home and have savings. If income is higher, asset limit is $4,500."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "They may still qualify through the net income test, which subtracts allowable deductions (like medical expenses over $35/month) from gross income. New York has more generous rules than many other states."
          },
          {
            "question": "My parent thinks they'll only get $16/month — is it worth applying?",
            "answer": "The average benefit for households with older adults in NYC is $180/month, not $16. The actual amount depends on income and expenses. Many seniors assume they'll get the minimum and don't apply, missing out on significant grocery assistance."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does my parent have to work to get SNAP?",
            "answer": "No work requirements for adults 65+. If your parent is 60-64 and not disabled, they must work 20 hours/week or earn $217.50/week, but volunteer hours may count toward this requirement."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent lives with adult children — does our income count?",
            "answer": "Only if you buy and prepare food together. If your parent buys and prepares meals separately, they can apply as a separate household. However, if the adult children's income exceeds 165% of poverty limit, separate household status isn't allowed."
          },
          {
            "question": "How long does SNAP last once approved?",
            "answer": "If your parent qualifies for ESAP (simplified application for seniors with no earned income), benefits last 36 months with minimal paperwork for renewal. Standard SNAP has shorter certification periods with more frequent renewals."
          }
